import java.util.*;

public List<Set<Integer>> twoLists(List<List<Integer>> matches) {
    Map<Integer, Integer> loss_count = new HashMap<>();
    Set<Integer> participants = new HashSet<>();

    for (List<Integer> match : matches) {
        int winner = match.get(0);
        int loser = match.get(1);
        loss_count.put(loser, loss_count.getOrDefault(loser, 0) + 1);
        participants.add(winner);
        participants.add(loser);
    }

    Set<Integer> no_losses = new TreeSet<>();
    Set<Integer> one_loss = new TreeSet<>();

    for (int participant : participants) {
        int count = loss_count.getOrDefault(participant, 0);
        if (count == 0) {
            no_losses.add(participant);
        } else if (count == 1) {
            one_loss.add(participant);
        }
    }

    return Arrays.asList(no_losses, one_loss);
}
```

    First, we create two data structures: a hash map to store the loss count of each participant, and a set to store all participants. For each match, increment the loss count for the loser and add both winner and loser to the participants set.

Next, we create two sets, one for participants with no losses and another for participants with exactly one loss. Go through each participant in the set and check their loss count. If a participant's loss count is zero or one, add them to the corresponding set.

Finally, return a list containing the no_losses and one_loss sets.
